lipsis-menu-semaphore-sign-in-redirect&guestReportContentType=POST&_f=guest-reporting)\n\n  South Africa's short-term insurance market generated roughly USD 11.9 billion in gross written premiums in 2024. The top ten companies controlled 58% of gross premiums (64% of insurance revenue). A combined ratio of 92.4% across the top ten suggests an industry in reasonable health, until you look at who is driving those numbers, and how differently they are doing it. Part I of this series mapped the market. In Part II, we ask the harder question: in a market this concentrated, why do the business models look so radically different from one another? What we found was not a monolith competing on price, but four distinct philosophies: -Traditional Broad-Line, - Direct-to-Consumer, - Platform/Cell Captive, and - Behavioral Innovation each with its own profit logic, its own risk assumptions, and its own answer to what sustainable insurance looks like. Santam holds roughly 19% of the market through scale and underwriting discipline. OUTsurance and King Price have turned distribution cost into a competitive weapon. Guardrisk has largely decoupled growth from capital consumption. Discovery is underwriting a thesis that human behaviour, if you can change it, is the most valuable risk variable of all, though the combined ratio suggests that thesis is still being proven. Some of these models generate profit through technical underwriting. Others depend on investment income, or in SASRIA's case, a legislative position that no competitor can replicate. The interesting question is not which model is winning right now. It is which one has the structural advantages to still be winning when the market looks different. Hope you enjoy the insights!\n\n  [64](https://www.linkedin.com/signup/cold-join?session_redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.linkedin.com%2Fposts%2Fyvonne-tendai-mujuru-6987961b_south-african-insurance-industry-four-models-activity-7449093723558387712-9j8V&trk=public_post_social-actions